---
const groupings = [
  {
    title: 'Agent swapping',
    body: 'One harness becomes many, chosen per task.',
  },
  {
    title: 'Individual to organization',
    body: 'Personal permissions and memory become shared, org-wide ones.',
  },
  {
    title: 'Increased collaboration',
    body: 'Solo sessions become multiplayer and durable.',
  },
  {
    title: 'Increased autonomy',
    body: 'The agent reaches across repos and remembers across time, so it stops handing work back to you.',
  },
];
---

<section id="recap" class="px-6 py-20 md:py-28">
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
    <p class="font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.25em] text-accent">
      The through-line
    </p>
    <h2
      class="mt-4 text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-neutral-50 sm:text-4xl"
    >
      It all comes back to autonomy
    </h2>
    <p class="mt-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-neutral-300">
      At bottom, a meta-harness looks for the
      <mark>moments where an agent would normally stop and hand the problem to
      a human</mark>, and lets the agent handle it instead. Almost everything
      above groups into four.
    </p>
    <p class="mt-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-neutral-400">
      The mechanism underneath is reification. A harness is so simple in scope
      that it is universally applicable, but that simplicity means the objects
      you actually work with, the organizations, users, sessions, repositories,
      code changes, and memories, are not first-class. Because they are not
      reified, the relationships between them are weak or nonexistent, and the
      agent hits walls a human has to resolve. A meta-harness
      <mark>makes them concrete objects</mark>: things you can name, pass around,
      and compose.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="mx-auto mt-10 grid max-w-5xl gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2">
    {
      groupings.map((g) => (
        <div class="rounded-lg border border-neutral-800 bg-neutral-900/30 p-6">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-medium text-neutral-100">{g.title}</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm leading-relaxed text-neutral-400">{g.body}</p>
        </div>
      ))
    }
  </div>

  <div class="mx-auto mt-10 max-w-3xl">
    <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-neutral-400">
      These capabilities are self-reinforcing. You can work around each gap on
      its own, but addressed together they compound, the way Next.js did once
      routing and server-side rendering were solved as one. And
      <mark>what an individual can work around, an organization cannot</mark>:
      there is no workaround for shared memory, and no workaround for durable
      sessions.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>
